  "output": "Confirmed: no React/frontend code exists â€” this is a pure Python async scraper/CLI (httpx + SQLite + PyYAML). I've reviewed all core modules (`store.py`, `pipeline.py`, `fetchers.py`, `models.py`, `filters.py`, `notify.py`, `agent.py`, `cli.py`). Here's the performance analysis with the categories mapped to what actually applies to this codebase.\n\n## Summary\n\nNo React exists in this repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply â€” I've substituted the closest equivalent problem class for a Python data pipeline (redundant per-item recomputation). Everything else maps directly.\n\n---\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern â€” `store.py:55-74` (the big one)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every job fetched in a run:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\",\n                          (job.key,)).fetchone()   # <-- 1 query per job\n        ...\n```\n\nSeveral fetchers pull thousands of listings per run (Microsoft/Amazon docstrings say \"the board is thousands of roles\"). That's thousands of round-trip `SELECT`s (each with sqlite3's per-call overhead) instead of one batched read.\n\n**Fix** â€” batch the lookup, diff in memory, then write with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(N/900) batched reads + 3 `executemany` calls.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Redundant computation â€” regex recompiled per job, not once â€” `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`_compile()` builds fresh `re.Pattern` objects from your include/exclude keyword lists **inside `match()`**, and `match()` is called once per job in `filter_jobs`'s list comprehension:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n    # -> match() calls _compile(include) and _compile(exclude) EVERY time\n```\n\nFor a run with, say, 5,000 fetched jobs and 15 keywords, that's 150,000 regex compilations instead of 30 (2 lists Ă— 15 patterns, compiled once).\n\n**Fix** â€” compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_p = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_p = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_p, exclude=exclude_p,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nThis is the single highest-value fix in the codebase â€” it's O(NĂ—M) â†’ O(M) and touches every run, every job.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Missing index â€” `store.py:111-119` (`added_since`, used by the agent scan flow)\n\n```python\ndef added_since(self, ts: str) -> list[sqlite3.Row]:\n    return self.conn.execute(\n        \"SELECT * FROM jobs WHERE first_seen > ? \"\n        \"ORDER BY first_seen, company, title\", (ts,)).fetchall()\n```\n\nOnly `idx_jobs_company` exists (store.py:27) â€” there's no index on `first_seen`, so this query does a full table scan + sort every time `agent.py db-new` runs, and `jobs.db` is explicitly a persistent, growing table across runs.\n\n**Fix**:\n\n```sql\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\nAdd to `_SCHEMA` in `store.py:10-32`, and it'll also let SQLite serve the `ORDER BY first_seen` for free.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Caching / concurrency opportunity â€” sequential pagination when the total is already known\n\n`fetch_workday` (fetchers.py:422-470) and `fetch_amazon` (fetchers.py:718-738) fetch pages **one at a time** in an `await`-in-a-`for`-loop, even though the *first* response already tells you the total result count (`data.get(\"total\")` for Workday; Amazon's payload includes a similar count field):\n\n```python\nwhile True:\n    data = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json=body, ...)\n    ...\n    total = data.get(\"total\", len(jobs))\n    offset += page_size\n    if not postings or offset >= total or offset > 5000:\n        break\n```\n\nOnce `total` is known after page 1, the remaining pages can be requested **concurrently** (bounded by a small semaphore) instead of serially â€” for a 2,000-role Amazon board at 10/page, that's 200 sequential round trips that could collapse to ~20 batches of 10 concurrent requests.\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    # ...first request as-is to learn `total`...\n    remaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\n    sem = asyncio.Semaphore(5)\n    async def _page(off):\n        async with sem:\n            body = {**base_body, \"offset\": off}\n            return await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json=body, ...)\n    pages = await asyncio.gather(*(_page(o) for o in remaining_offsets))\n    for data in pages:\n        jobs.extend(parse(data.get(\"jobPostings\", [])))\n```\n\nSources that genuinely can't know the total up front (Google's `ds:1` blob, Two Sigma, Optiver â€” they signal \"done\" only by an empty page) have to stay sequential; this only applies where the API already reports a count.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Blocking I/O inside an async pipeline â€” `notify.py`\n\n`notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, and `notify_sms` call synchronous `httpx.post(...)` (not `httpx.AsyncClient`), and `notify_email` uses blocking `smtplib`. `dispatch()` is invoked from `pipeline.run()` (an `async def`), so these block the event loop thread during the call:\n\n```python\ndef notify_slack(new, changed) -> None:\n    ...\n    httpx.post(url, json={\"text\": text}, timeout=15)   # blocking call inside async pipeline\n```\n\nCurrently harmless because nothing else is scheduled concurrently at that point in the run, but it's a latent footgun if `dispatch()` is ever called alongside other async work (e.g., a future watch-mode loop). If that need ever comes up, swap to a shared `httpx.AsyncClient` and `await client.post(...)`.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Minor redundant computation â€” `Job.content_hash` recomputed twice per row\n\n`content_hash` (models.py:66-69) is a plain `@property` doing a SHA-256 hash â€” it's computed once in `Store.diff()`'s comparison and again inside `to_row()` when `_insert`/`_update` runs for the same job. Cheap individually (a 4-field hash), but it's dead-simple to avoid by computing the row dict once and reusing it:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs):\n    ...\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = job.to_row()  # compute once, includes content_hash\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append(row)\n        elif prev != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append(row)\n```\n\nNot worth a standalone fix â€” fold it into the N+1 batching rewrite above (#1) since that already restructures this loop.\n\n---\n\n## What I did *not* find\n\n- **Memory leaks**: none of real concern â€” this is a short-lived CLI process (fetch â†’ filter â†’ dedup â†’ notify â†’ exit), not a long-running server, so there's no accumulating state across requests. `Job.raw` holds full per-job payloads in memory for the run's duration, but it's dropped when the process exits; only worth revisiting if this ever becomes a long-running daemon.\n- **React re-renders**: N/A â€” no frontend code exists in this repo (confirmed via `find` for `.tsx`/`.jsx`/`.vue`, none found).\n\n**Priority order**: #2 (regex recompilation) and #1 (N+1 store.diff) are the two that scale with job-board size and run on every single invocation â€” fix those first. #3 (index) is a one-line schema addition. #4 is worth it only if you're hitting the biggest boards (Amazon/Microsoft) often enough that pagination latency matters.\n",
